Staff members sang carols as food hampers were handed out to 840 in-patients Thursday. Gafsa Hendricks said she had come into the hospital about three weeks ago with pain in her legs. “They have done such a good job with me. "They did a huge investigation and afterwards they realised that the nerves in my legs are damaged and now they have been treating me with a cancer treatment." To view this video please enable JavaScript, and consider upgrading to a web browser that
    supports HTML5 video This is a modal window. Beginning of dialog window. Escape will cancel and close the window. End of dialog window. She said being in hospital was not a cheerful time but said the hospital was good in making them feel better, in more ways than one. “This is amazing, I am so emotional. I may not be Christian but I feel so emotional about the baskets they gave and the singing and happiness really strikes home.” Nabawia Arend suffers from emphysema and has been at the hospital from Monday. “They are trying their very best and I feel I am in very capable hands. It’s so nice of them to come and cheer us up.” She said not many wanted to waste their time caring for others and she was very appreciative about what they hospital did for them. Christo Abrahams has been at the hospital for a week, for kidney failure, and commended the staff for making the time festive. “Being here this time is different; I miss my family really. It's my second time not being with them. Last year this time I was also in the hospital. The staff here doesn’t make you feel left out and they make you feel like a family.” Groote Schuur spokesperson Alaric Jacobs said the initiative had been started four years ago by the hospital's facility board. To view this video please enable JavaScript, and consider upgrading to a web browser that
    supports HTML5 video This is a modal window. Beginning of dialog window. Escape will cancel and close the window. End of dialog window. He said they had packed 840 bags that were handed over to their inpatients. “It’s very stressful to be in hospital when everyone else is having a good time and celebrating the festive season. Some of them don’t even get visitors or gifts this time of the year, so they get very emotional when we hand them the packs. For some of them this is the only gift they get. “The staff walk around singing carols on Christmas; the patients get a special lunch and different departments trim the areas just to get the festive mood and patients get that festive mood around them.”  yolisa.tswanya@inl.co.za  Cape Argus